TY  - JOUR
T1  - A Multilevel Model of Privatization in Emerging Economies
AU  - Ramamurti, Ravi
Y1  - 2000/07/01
PY  - 2000
DA  - 2000/07/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2000.3363509
DO  - 10.5465/amr.2000.3363509
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 525
EP  - 550
VL  - 25
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Why are so many emerging economies privatizing state-owned enterprises, and how does that affect their performance? The author proposes a dynamic multilevel model to answer these questions. Firm-level arguments need to be complemented by industry- and country-level arguments to explain why some enterprises are privatized but not others. Similarly, changes in firm governance resulting from privatization are only one determinant of postprivatization performance: changes in industry structure, regulation, and country-level variables are as important. Furthermore, changes introduced at all three levels in one round of reform influence the context within which subsequent privatizations occur.
AB  - Why are so many emerging economies privatizing state-owned enterprises, and how does that affect their performance? The author proposes a dynamic multilevel model to answer these questions. Firm-level arguments need to be complemented by industry- and country-level arguments to explain why some enterprises are privatized but not others. Similarly, changes in firm governance resulting from privatization are only one determinant of postprivatization performance: changes in industry structure, regulation, and country-level variables are as important. Furthermore, changes introduced at all three levels in one round of reform influence the context within which subsequent privatizations occur.
SN  - 0363-7425
M3  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2000.3363509
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/amr.2000.3363509
Y2  - 2026/04/24
